    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nCommenting prioritizes treesitter injected languages' filetypes' `'commentstring'` over other sources, which may be incorrect.\r\nFor example if one has [nvim-treesitter](https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter) installed and editing a markdown file and `vim.treesitter.language.get_filetypes('markdown')` returns a table where the filetype `quarto` or `rmd` is after `markdown` then the `'commentstring'` used will be `quarto/rmd`'s `'commentstring'` which is `# %s` instead of `markdown`'s commentstring which is `<!--%s-->`.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim --clean foo.md\r\n:lua vim.treesitter.language.add('markdown',{filetype='rmd'})\r\n:lua vim.treesitter.start()\r\nabar<esc>\r\ngcc\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThe appropriate `'commentstring'` being used.\r\n\r\nOne solution for solving this problem would be: if any of a treesitter language's filetypes match the current filetype then use the buffer-local `'commentstring'`.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nv0.10.0-dev-624de84\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nlinux 6.8.4-arch1-1\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkitty 0.33.1\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-kitty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nbuild from repo",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Not sure I want to add this extra complexity for such a snowflake situation. If two languages share a parser, they should share a syntax, and that includes the syntax for comments. I'd rather remove the extra filetypes in nvim-treesitter if this assumption is incorrect for them.",
